
2.  Synopsys Commands                                        Command Reference
                             set_track_constraint

NAME
       set_track_constraint
              Defines  a set of track constraints on per-layer basis. The con-
              straints describe rules for the structure of  track  objects  in
              the block to ensure that the generate wire tracks meet the manu-
              facturability criteria.

SYNTAX
       integer set_track_constraint
              [-block block]
              [-space space]
              [-label label]
              -layers layers
              [-mask masks]
              [-offset offsets]
              -relative_to block | core_area
              [-dir horizontal | vertical | Y | X]
              [-first_row_orientation R0 | MX]
              [-widths widths]
              [-mask_pattern masks]
              [-end_grid_low_offset offset]
              [-end_grid_high_offset offset]
              [-end_grid_low_steps offsets]
              [-end_grid_high_steps offsets]
              [-append]

   Data Types
       block    string
       space     integer
       label    string
       layers   string
       masks    list of masks
       offset   distance
       offsets  list of distances
       widths   format list of widths

ARGUMENTS
       -block block
              An optional argument specifying the block on which  to  set  the
              track  constraints.  By default the command operates on the cur-
              rent block.

       -spacespace
              An optional argument specifying the length of the window for the
              allowable  track  offset pattern. If no value is given, the tool
              will check the pitch setting for the  corresponding  tech  layer
              and error if none exists.

       -label label
              An  optional argument specifying the label assigned to the track
              constraint definition generated by the command. Labels  must  be
              unique, but might apply to multiple track constraint classifica-
              tions if more than one is covered in the constraints definition.
              The  exception to this rule is the default label which is empty.
              The default label may be used any number of times.

       -layers layer
              A required argument specifying the layers for  which  the  track
              constraints apply.  Only valid interconnect layers may be given,
              and the commad will set the given constraint on each of the lay-
              ers.

       -mask masks
              An  optional  argument  specifying  the masks for which the con-
              straint applies. Mask values currently supported are  "mask_one"
              and "mask_two". The constraint applies only to tracks that exist
              on the given masks. Giving  a  list  with  both  "mask_one"  and
              "mask_two"  means  the  constraint  applies  to  tracks  on both
              mask_one and mask_two. Mutually exclusive with -mask_pattern.

              Omitting the -mask argument assigns the constraint to  uncolored
              tracks. This argument is mutually exclusive with -mask_pattern.

       -offset offset
              An  optional  argument  specifying  the  allowable positions for
              tracks relative to a multiple of the constraint window or  spac-
              ing  value.  The list should contain only floating-point numbers
              in increasing order. The list  should  not  contain  any  values
              greater  than  the value given for the -space argument. The list
              may contain only one number  which  indicates  a  uniform  track
              spacing. The default value is 0.

       -relative_to block | core_area
              A required argument specifying the reference point for the track
              constraint pattern defined. A value of "block"  means  the  con-
              straint  pattern  starts from the boundary of the block. A value
              of "core_area" means the  constraint  pattern  starts  from  the
              boundary of the block's core area.

       -dir horizontal | vertical | Y | X
              An  optional  argument  specifying the track direction for which
              the constraint applies.  A value of "horizontal"  or  "Y"  means
              the  constraint applies only to tracks parallel to the x-axis. A
              value of "vertical" or "X" means the constraint applies only  to
              tracks  parallel to the y-axis. Omitting this argument means the
              constraint applies to both horizontal and vertical tracks.

       -first_row_orientation R0 | MX
              An optional argument designating  which  first  row  orientation
              values  the given constraint applies to. The default behavior is
              to apply to both R0 and MX row orientations. You might set sepa-
              rate constraints for each of R0, MX, and "R0 MX".

       -widths widths
              An  optional  argument specifying a pattern of track widths. The
              widths apply to tracks following the pattern of offsets. So  the
              first  width applies to the track at the first offset, and so on
              repeating across the constraint space.  In  typical  usage,  the
              number  of  widths  will  match the number of offsets. If a con-
              straint has multiple offsets and only one width value, the width
              will be expanded to apply to each offset.

              The syntax for the argument is a list of distances with optional
              repeats. So each list element may either be a standard  distance
              value  or  a  pair  of  a  distance  and a repeat, designated by
              "{<distance> r<num>}". An example widths value is "0.011  {0.022
              r4} 0.011", which describes a 6-element width list starting with
              0.011, followed by 4 0.022, and ending with 0.011. The user  may
              also enumerate each 0.022 value if desired.

       -mask_pattern masks
              An  optional  argument  specifying  an order of masks to follow.
              Whereas -mask specifies which mask to constrain,  this  argument
              specifies  the  order of masks in a constraint.  Mutually exclu-
              sive with -mask.

       -end_grid_low_offset offset
              An optional argument to specify the offset from the left or bot-
              tom edge to the starting point of the first grid rectangle.

       -end_grid_high_offset offset
              An optional argument to specify the offset from the left or bot-
              tom edge to the ending point of the first grid rectangle.

       -end_grid_low_steps offsets
              An optional argument to specify a list of steps to use when cre-
              ating  subsequent  grid  points.  Each offset in the list is the
              distance between the previous starting grid point and  the  cur-
              rent starting grid point.

       -end_grid_high_steps offsets
              An optional argument to specify a list of steps to use when cre-
              ating subsequent grid points. Each offset in  the  list  is  the
              distance  between the previous ending grid point and the current
              ending grid point.

       -append
              Specifies whether or not to add the defined  constraint  to  the
              current set or to override the first constraint in the list. The
              legacy behavior for the command always performed an override  on
              the  first constraint as only 1 constraint was allowed per track
              classification. As such the default behavior is override.

DESCRIPTION
       The set_track_constraint command defines valid wire track structures in
       the  given  block  on  a per-layer basis. The constraint itself is com-
       prised of an origin, spacing, and offset. The origin describes the ref-
       erence  point  from  which to start the pattern, the boundary of either
       the block or the core area. The constraint pattern itself is defined as
       each  offset value starting from each multiple of the spacing value. In
       other words, the constraint pattern says that tracks are valid if  they
       exist  at  a  location given by the expression O + n*G + F for any F in
       the offset list.

       The defined constraint applies to the tracks specified  by  the  block,
       layer, dir, and mask arguments.

       Lastly,  the  label  serves  as an identifier for the given constraint.
       Labels may not be reused after they have been applied, with the  excep-
       tion of the empty (default) label.  The same constraint might, however,
       be overwritten with a different label.  Constraints  and  their  corre-
       sponding labels might be removed using the remove_track_constraint com-
       mand.  After a label has been removed (which happened by  removing  all
       constraints  covered by that label) it might be reassigned to a new set
       of constraints.

EXAMPLES
       The following command creates a constraint that applies to both  verti-
       cal  and  horizontal tracks with a mask color of 1 on layer M1 in block
       current_block. The constraint says that valid tracks can exist at  off-
       set  values of 0, 0.2, 0.8, 1, 1.2, 1.8, 2, and so on.  from the bound-
       ary of the block.
         prompt> set_track_constraint -block [current_block] -layer M1 \
            -label A -space 1 -offset {0 0.2 0.8} -relative_to block -mask mask_one

       The following command creates a constraint that applies  to  horizontal
       tracks  on  layers  M2  and  M3 relative to the core area boundary. The
       tracks may be at offsets of 0.2 or 0.5 every 5 units. The track  widths
       must  follow the pattern "0.02 0.03" repeated, and the track masks must
       follow the pattern "mask_one mask_two" repeated. The tracks  must  have
       the specified end_grid settings.
         prompt> set_track_constraint -layers "M2 M3" -relative_to core_area -dir X -offset "0.2 0.5" \
             -widths "0.02 0.03" -mask_pattern "MASK_ONE MASK_TWO" -end_grid_low_offset 2 -end_grid_high_offset 4 \
             -end_grid_low_steps { 1 3 } -end_grid_high_steps { 1 4 }

SEE ALSO
       remove_track_constraint(2)
       report_track_constraints(2)

